    <title>Combined summary - Generalized covenants with taproot enable riskless or risky lending, prevent credit inflation through fractional reserve</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T19:49:36.502862+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-June/017062.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email exchange discusses the potential of covenants in Bitcoin transactions and the importance of full reserve banking. Tamas Blummer proposes a covenant construct for loans with full reserve checks, ensuring the lender's coins are unconditionally returned at maturity through encumbering them with a taproot path of validation. The email also explores the idea of returning to full reserve banking and published a writing on fractional vs. full reserve banking in conjunction with this proposal. Covenants in Bitcoin transactions allow certain conditions to be attached to the transfer of funds, and the author provides examples of how covenants could be used to temporarily transfer control of coins and how different parties could benefit from them.The conversation also touches upon the market value of Bitcoin, with Eric Voskuil arguing that for something to have marketable value, it must be both scarce and useful, while Tamas Blummer argues that the deeper utility of Bitcoin lies in its unforgeable register and suggests creating other kinds of units through covenants that are encumbered but not fungible with common ones. Overall, the email exchange encourages further exploration and collaboration in this area, and provides links to resources for further investigation.Another topic discussed in the emails is the proposed "Bitcoin Classified Ads Network" (BCAN) and how it could be a crucial design pattern to build censorship-resistant networks that give rise to riskless interest on Bitcoin. The nodes in BCAN gossip advertisements, referring to a UTXO that must be unspent at the chain tip considered by each node. Advertisements must contain a commitment to the text of the advertisement, and nodes have a maximum limit on the total size of all advertisements they retain and propagate to new nodes. The email thread discusses various ways to impose costs on use without direct billing, such as burning Bitcoins, time-locking own Bitcoins, paying someone else to time-lock, transferable borrowed Bitcoin, and "renting a UTXO of substantial value." The participants also explore the concept of using unspentness-time of a UTXO for advertising services or producers, which allows for time-based hedging for merchants.Bitcoin developer Tamas Blummer believes that an unforgeable register is essential for something to acquire value, and the security of that ownership register influences the value. He proposes using covenants in Bitcoin transactions, which allow certain conditions to be attached to the transfer of funds. The covenant-supported temporary access is transitive, meaning that anyone in temporary control of a UTXO can recover its cost by sub-renting. This provides a baseline of value on top of which there may be utility in the advertisement. Additionally, the email conversations discuss the potential of covenants in Bitcoin transactions and their importance in solving problems that cannot currently be solved through other means. The deeper utility of Bitcoin is its unforgeable register which can be used to create different kinds of units that are not fungible with common ones.The email conversation between Tamas Blummer and Eric Voskuil discusses the value of coins encumbered with a covenant, representing temporary control of a scarce resource. The ability to deal with temporary control and availability of final control determine the value of such coins. In areas where final control is not available, people pay high prices to step in place of the renter in existing long-term rent contracts. Bitcoin's predominant use is already store of value, leading to unwillingness to give up final control that can resolve in two ways; increasing fiat prices for final control or dealing with temporary control, which does not have technical means yet. Blummer discusses different ways to impose costs on use without direct billing, including burning Bitcoins to use the service, paying high fees in self-dealing transactions, time-locking own Bitcoins, paying someone else to time-lock, and transferable borrowed Bitcoin. They also discussed the concept of "rent" and how the cost of encumbrance includes at least one transaction fee and market cost of the coin rental.During a recent Bitcoin research and development meeting, the topic of generalized covenants was discussed along with its viability as a use case. However, Eric Voskuil did not fully support this idea as he believed it was already possible on current Bitcoin. ZmnSCPxj presented another use case involving a "Bitcoin Classified Ads Network" where advertisements are backed by an unspent TXO. The email author critiqued Eric's cryproeconomic theories stating that they accurately describe Bitcoin as money but fail to account for reliable memory for other uses. The finite supply of coins means that there is a finite memory capacity, making units temporarily unfungible which leads to competition for units of memory and a price paid to those enabling alternate use. The author suggests designing systems to sustain Bitcoin for as long as possible while avoiding burning for any unlimited number of uses. Finally, the author concludes that Bitcoin is different from borrowed money which is fungible with other money since it just exists without being borrowed into existence.</summary>
